SIMPLE: nasty
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Nasty
<hw>Nas"ty</hw> <pr>(n⟦adot⟧s"t⟦ycr⟧)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Nastier</adjf>
<pr>(n⟦adot⟧s"t⟦icr⟧*⟦etil⟧r)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Nastiest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[For older <ets>nasky</ets>; cf.
dial. Sw. <ets>naskug</ets>, <ets>nasket</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Offensively filthy; very dirty, foul, or defiled; disgusting;
nauseous.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, loosely: Offensive; disagreeable;
unpropitious; wet; drizzling; <as>as, a <ex>nasty</ex> rain, day,
sky</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Characterized by obscenity; indecent; indelicate;
gross; filthy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Vicious; offensively ill-tempered; insultingly mean;
spiteful; <as>as, a <ex>nasty</ex> disposition</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Difficult to deal with; troublesome; <as>as, he fell
of his bike and got a <ex>nasty</ex> bruise on his knee</as>.</def>
<mark>[slang]</mark> ⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- <er>Nasty</er>, <er>Filthy</er>, <er>Foul</er>,
<er>Dirty</er>.</syn> <usage>Anything <xex>nasty</xex> is usually wet or
damp as well as filthy or dirty, and disgusts by its stickiness or odor;
but <xex>filthy</xex> and <xex>foul</xex> imply that a thing is filled
or covered with offensive matter, while <xex>dirty</xex> describes it as
defiled or sullied with dirt of any kind; as, <xex>filthy</xex>
clothing, <xex>foul</xex> vapors, etc.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Nasute</ent>⟦br⟧
